1
00:00:08,530 --> 00:00:10,097
[ Grunts ]

2
00:00:37,994 --> 00:00:39,343
OK.

3
00:00:40,475 --> 00:00:41,824
Let's do it!

4
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:50,659
Are you there?

5
00:00:50,789 --> 00:00:52,617
[ Clanging ]

6
00:00:53,966 --> 00:00:55,055
[ Thunder ]

7
00:01:09,373 --> 00:01:10,722
[ Loud thunderclap ]

8
00:01:17,599 --> 00:01:19,035
Show yourself, please!

9
00:01:19,166 --> 00:01:20,080
[ Crashing ]

10
00:01:41,449 --> 00:01:42,885
This can't go on!

11
00:01:48,369 --> 00:01:50,849
I've waited way too long
to face you!

12
00:01:54,418 --> 00:01:56,594
This should have been settled
a long time ago!

13
00:02:00,946 --> 00:02:03,645
Please! Let's end this!

14
00:02:03,775 --> 00:02:05,821
I'm willing to do anything!

15
00:02:17,963 --> 00:02:19,487
[ Thunderclap ]

16
00:02:19,617 --> 00:02:21,141
There must be a way!

17
00:02:25,536 --> 00:02:26,624
No!

18
00:02:27,843 --> 00:02:29,018
N-no!

19
00:02:29,149 --> 00:02:30,759
NO!

20
00:02:30,889 --> 00:02:32,674
[ Screaming ]

21
00:02:49,473 --> 00:02:50,953
Oh, I can't do this.

22
00:02:51,083 --> 00:02:52,172
Do what?

23
00:02:53,651 --> 00:02:55,827
This! Just being here!

24
00:02:55,958 --> 00:02:57,655
I feel so vulnerable.

25
00:02:57,786 --> 00:02:59,527
Where's George?

26
00:02:59,657 --> 00:03:02,704
I don't know, but he better
be dead or dying somewhere.

27
00:03:02,834 --> 00:03:04,358
I can't believe he's not here!

28
00:03:04,488 --> 00:03:06,882
It's early!
He'll make it, don't worry.

29
00:03:07,012 --> 00:03:09,363
In the meantime, relax!
They're gonna love you!

30
00:03:09,493 --> 00:03:10,973
I don't want them to love me.

31
00:03:11,103 --> 00:03:12,540
I want them
to love my paintings.

32
00:03:17,109 --> 00:03:18,894
OK, Nick, you need to get over

33
00:03:19,024 --> 00:03:20,548
this whole
tortured artist thing.

34
00:03:20,678 --> 00:03:22,550
I mean, look at me!
You don't see me

35
00:03:22,680 --> 00:03:24,987
worried about what the critics
write about my plays.

36
00:03:25,117 --> 00:03:27,294
Because you haven't had
any produced yet, Margie.

37
00:03:27,424 --> 00:03:28,860
Minor detail!
The point is,

38
00:03:28,991 --> 00:03:31,211
I don't write for the
critics, I write for myself.

39
00:03:31,341 --> 00:03:32,864
So if they hated your plays,

40
00:03:32,995 --> 00:03:34,997
you'd just be content
and keep writing them?

41
00:03:35,127 --> 00:03:36,346
Yeah, of course I would!

42
00:03:36,477 --> 00:03:37,521
That is such a lie.

43
00:03:37,652 --> 00:03:39,175
Two things you need

44
00:03:39,306 --> 00:03:42,004
more than anyone else
I know are love and money.

45
00:03:42,134 --> 00:03:43,048
Hmm.

46
00:03:43,179 --> 00:03:44,528
Here she is!

47
00:03:44,659 --> 00:03:46,878
The star of the evening,
Nicky Wickersham.

48
00:03:47,009 --> 00:03:49,881
Although after tonight,
she'll be known only as Nicky.

49
00:03:50,012 --> 00:03:51,840
Oh! Well,

50
00:03:51,970 --> 00:03:54,059
you're assuming
that I'll survive the night.

51
00:03:54,190 --> 00:03:56,105
It's first-show jitters.

52
00:03:56,236 --> 00:03:58,238
Nicky, you know Darren Peters?

53
00:03:58,368 --> 00:04:01,066
One of Boston's most
important art critics.

54
00:04:01,197 --> 00:04:02,416
How do you do?

55
00:04:02,546 --> 00:04:04,548
The... oh, sorry.
This is my friend,

56
00:04:04,679 --> 00:04:05,636
Margie Mancuso.

57
00:04:05,767 --> 00:04:06,637
It's a pleasure.

58
00:04:06,768 --> 00:04:07,899
Pleasure's all mine.

59
00:04:08,030 --> 00:04:10,075
I understand the first
axiom of an art show

60
00:04:10,206 --> 00:04:12,034
is "never ask
a critic what he thinks."

61
00:04:12,164 --> 00:04:15,385
[Chuckling]:
Well, I think that...

62
00:04:15,516 --> 00:04:18,432
Celia has unearthed,
shall I say, another...

63
00:04:18,562 --> 00:04:20,564
marketable jewel.

64
00:04:22,087 --> 00:04:23,524
Well, let's just hope

65
00:04:23,654 --> 00:04:26,004
the market goes
bullish on jewels.

66
00:04:26,135 --> 00:04:27,136
[ Chuckling ]

67
00:04:27,267 --> 00:04:28,616
Well, we'll know early Monday,

68
00:04:28,746 --> 00:04:30,487
when Darren's review
hits the stands!

69
00:04:30,618 --> 00:04:32,750
Oh, I don't think
you'll have to wait that long.

70
00:04:32,881 --> 00:04:34,186
Would you ladies excuse me?

71
00:04:34,317 --> 00:04:35,492
Yeah.

72
00:04:37,146 --> 00:04:38,278
He hates me.

73
00:04:38,408 --> 00:04:40,236
What are you talking about?

74
00:04:40,367 --> 00:04:41,629
He was eyeballing you

75
00:04:41,759 --> 00:04:43,587
like you were
the only porterhouse

76
00:04:43,718 --> 00:04:44,588
at a tofu picnic!

77
00:04:44,719 --> 00:04:46,155
Tell her, Celia.

78
00:04:46,286 --> 00:04:48,592
Would you try to look
as if you want to be here?

79
00:04:48,723 --> 00:04:51,116
Believe it or not, people
don't want to buy paintings

80
00:04:51,247 --> 00:04:53,031
off an artist who can't
look at her own work!

81
00:04:53,162 --> 00:04:54,816
I love my work.

82
00:04:54,946 --> 00:04:57,253
Well, tell them, not me!

83
00:04:58,950 --> 00:05:00,343
What does that mean?

84
00:05:00,474 --> 00:05:03,085
I... I think
what she's saying

85
00:05:03,215 --> 00:05:06,306
is the only difference between
an artist and a prostitute

86
00:05:06,436 --> 00:05:07,655
is what they're selling.

87
00:05:07,785 --> 00:05:09,134
And I'm not selling?

88
00:05:09,265 --> 00:05:10,919
Name your price!

89
00:05:11,049 --> 00:05:12,355
Damn the critics!

90
00:05:15,576 --> 00:05:16,707
You're late.

91
00:05:16,838 --> 00:05:19,144
The market dropped
200 points at closing.

92
00:05:19,275 --> 00:05:20,755
We were losing a fortune!

93
00:05:20,885 --> 00:05:22,409
Steven didn't want me to leave,

94
00:05:22,539 --> 00:05:24,628
but I told him I had
more pressing business

95
00:05:24,759 --> 00:05:27,892
than, you know, half
a million investors.

96
00:05:28,023 --> 00:05:30,373
Well, those are the instincts

97
00:05:30,504 --> 00:05:32,462
that make you a good
investment broker.

98
00:05:32,593 --> 00:05:33,637
Hmm!

99
00:05:33,768 --> 00:05:36,336
Now you, go work the room!

100
00:05:36,466 --> 00:05:38,860
Huh? Get out there.

101
00:05:40,209 --> 00:05:41,297
[ Grunts ]

102
00:05:41,428 --> 00:05:42,777
[ Chuckles ]

103
00:05:50,437 --> 00:05:52,569
A toast...

104
00:05:52,700 --> 00:05:55,485
To the most beautiful
woman in all of Boston,

105
00:05:55,616 --> 00:05:57,792
and the man lucky enough

106
00:05:57,922 --> 00:06:00,142
to be her husband for 365 days.

107
00:06:00,272 --> 00:06:04,276
Mmm, 361. Our
anniversary is next week.

108
00:06:04,407 --> 00:06:05,321
Ah...

109
00:06:06,627 --> 00:06:07,671
Oh!

110
00:06:07,802 --> 00:06:09,673
I was saving this

111
00:06:09,804 --> 00:06:11,458
till next week, but...

112
00:06:12,763 --> 00:06:14,722
Seeing you work
that room tonight...

113
00:06:16,245 --> 00:06:17,333
Happy anniversary.

114
00:06:17,464 --> 00:06:18,682
George!

115
00:06:18,813 --> 00:06:19,901
Oh, go on, open it.

116
00:06:20,031 --> 00:06:21,206
OK.

117
00:06:23,818 --> 00:06:24,775
[ Chuckling ]

118
00:06:29,780 --> 00:06:31,042
It's a brooch!

119
00:06:32,217 --> 00:06:33,436
You don't like it.

120
00:06:33,567 --> 00:06:35,133
[Chuckling]: No!

121
00:06:35,264 --> 00:06:36,657
I mean, honestly,

122
00:06:36,787 --> 00:06:38,702
it's like nothing
I've ever seen before!

123
00:06:38,833 --> 00:06:40,182
Oh, come on, Nicky!

124
00:06:40,312 --> 00:06:42,663
That's just a nice way
of saying that you hate it!

125
00:06:42,793 --> 00:06:45,230
No, George!
It's... I just...

126
00:06:45,361 --> 00:06:48,146
I didn't expect for you
to buy me a brooch.

127
00:06:48,277 --> 00:06:50,192
I didn't!
Well, buy it.

128
00:06:50,322 --> 00:06:52,499
It's... it's a family heirloom.

129
00:06:52,629 --> 00:06:55,632
It's been passed down
for almost 200 years,

130
00:06:55,763 --> 00:06:59,157
and judging by your reaction,

131
00:06:59,288 --> 00:07:02,160
that tradition is
soon to be eradicated!

132
00:07:02,291 --> 00:07:03,684
Ouch!

133
00:07:03,814 --> 00:07:05,207
No, I love it,

134
00:07:05,337 --> 00:07:07,818
and I think that
it is very beautiful.

135
00:07:07,949 --> 00:07:10,560
OK, now you're just
lying out of guilt.

136
00:07:11,692 --> 00:07:13,041
I love it.

137
00:07:13,171 --> 00:07:15,435
And I'm gonna prove it to you.

138
00:07:16,914 --> 00:07:18,786
Well, how are you gonna do that?

139
00:07:18,916 --> 00:07:19,917
Mmm!

140
00:07:21,049 --> 00:07:22,529
Like this.

141
00:07:22,659 --> 00:07:24,095
[ Chuckling ]

142
00:07:24,226 --> 00:07:25,619
Oh!

143
00:07:29,492 --> 00:07:31,059
[ Laughing ]

144
00:07:47,945 --> 00:07:49,294
Good morning!

145
00:07:49,425 --> 00:07:51,296
Great morning!

146
00:07:51,427 --> 00:07:52,776
[Both]: Mmm!

147
00:07:54,430 --> 00:07:56,127
What got into you last night?

148
00:07:56,258 --> 00:07:57,564
[ Chuckling ]

149
00:07:57,694 --> 00:08:00,741
You. And a bottle
of champagne.

150
00:08:00,871 --> 00:08:02,264
Oh. Well...

151
00:08:02,394 --> 00:08:04,092
I have to get you
drunk more often!

152
00:08:04,222 --> 00:08:05,615
Don't count on it!

153
00:08:05,746 --> 00:08:07,312
Once a year is
good enough for me.

154
00:08:10,011 --> 00:08:11,316
Hey!

155
00:08:11,447 --> 00:08:13,623
Didn't anyone ever
tell you that it's rude

156
00:08:13,754 --> 00:08:16,104
to run out on a girl
first thing in the morning

157
00:08:16,234 --> 00:08:18,846
after she worked as hard
as I did last night?

158
00:08:18,976 --> 00:08:20,761
I have to get to work early.

159
00:08:20,891 --> 00:08:22,545
Our big hitters took a bath,

160
00:08:22,676 --> 00:08:24,329
and Steven is gonna
be all over me

161
00:08:24,460 --> 00:08:26,288
to get it back by
the end of the day.

162
00:08:26,418 --> 00:08:28,508
He puts too much
pressure on you.

163
00:08:28,638 --> 00:08:31,423
Well, it's called
responsibility.

164
00:08:31,554 --> 00:08:32,947
And I like it.

165
00:08:33,077 --> 00:08:34,165
Hmm.

166
00:08:37,255 --> 00:08:38,518
[ Sighs ]

167
00:08:41,390 --> 00:08:42,347
[ Sighs ]

168
00:08:50,181 --> 00:08:51,531
I...

169
00:08:51,661 --> 00:08:53,010
[ Groans ]

170
00:09:00,061 --> 00:09:01,671
Don't mess with my head, Celia.

171
00:09:01,802 --> 00:09:02,977
Was it good or bad?

172
00:09:03,107 --> 00:09:03,891
It was good!

173
00:09:04,021 --> 00:09:05,327
And bad.

174
00:09:05,457 --> 00:09:06,502
[ Sighs ]

175
00:09:06,633 --> 00:09:07,895
They didn't like it.

176
00:09:08,025 --> 00:09:09,200
Oh, relax, Nicky.

177
00:09:09,331 --> 00:09:10,637
It was a good first show.

178
00:09:10,767 --> 00:09:12,464
You impressed all
the right people,

179
00:09:12,595 --> 00:09:14,118
but there were
just some concerns

180
00:09:14,249 --> 00:09:15,337
about your staying power.

181
00:09:15,467 --> 00:09:17,121
So are you saying

182
00:09:17,252 --> 00:09:19,036
that the critics didn't...

183
00:09:19,167 --> 00:09:20,429
No, no, certainly not.

184
00:09:20,560 --> 00:09:22,213
Oh no, Dylan.
That's too high.

185
00:09:22,344 --> 00:09:24,868
Bring it down,
so we can light the corners.

186
00:09:26,130 --> 00:09:28,002
Anyway, I think it's fair to say

187
00:09:28,132 --> 00:09:29,830
that the critics were bemused.

188
00:09:29,960 --> 00:09:31,135
[ Scoffs ]

189
00:09:31,266 --> 00:09:32,528
Bemused?

190
00:09:32,659 --> 00:09:35,226
Yeah, well, they don't
know what to make of you!

191
00:09:35,357 --> 00:09:38,055
They can see your talent, but
they question your commitment.

192
00:09:39,317 --> 00:09:40,536
[ Sighs ]

193
00:09:41,798 --> 00:09:44,105
It's all about
ego and reputation.

194
00:09:44,235 --> 00:09:47,064
Everyone wants to find
the next big thing,

195
00:09:47,195 --> 00:09:50,546
but no one wants to risk
their reputation finding it.

196
00:09:50,677 --> 00:09:52,635
And you didn't help matters

197
00:09:52,766 --> 00:09:54,898
with your introverted
behaviour last night.

198
00:09:57,161 --> 00:10:00,077
I'm just really uncomfortable

199
00:10:00,208 --> 00:10:02,297
talking about my art!

200
00:10:02,427 --> 00:10:05,866
I don't want you to talk
about your art with the critics!

201
00:10:05,996 --> 00:10:08,172
Talk about sex,
drugs, rock 'n' roll.

202
00:10:08,303 --> 00:10:09,913
Show them your passion,

203
00:10:10,044 --> 00:10:11,611
and they will
talk about your art.

204
00:10:12,786 --> 00:10:14,178
Remember something.

205
00:10:14,309 --> 00:10:16,659
Critics survive by destroying

206
00:10:16,790 --> 00:10:18,356
more careers than they create.

207
00:10:18,487 --> 00:10:19,880
Go away,

208
00:10:20,010 --> 00:10:23,187
and paint something that
grabs you by the throat.

209
00:10:23,318 --> 00:10:25,668
Or the crotch.
I don't care.

210
00:10:25,799 --> 00:10:28,628
Your next show is much more
important than your last one.

211
00:10:28,758 --> 00:10:30,064
It always is!

212
00:10:30,194 --> 00:10:32,240
My next show?

213
00:10:32,370 --> 00:10:33,589
Of course.

214
00:10:34,764 --> 00:10:36,244
I'm gonna make you famous

215
00:10:36,374 --> 00:10:38,246
no matter how much
you fight it. Now go!

216
00:10:50,998 --> 00:10:52,303
Hey!

217
00:10:52,434 --> 00:10:54,523
What are you
doing home so early?

218
00:11:00,747 --> 00:11:02,052
What happened?

219
00:11:07,057 --> 00:11:08,232
My, um...

220
00:11:09,625 --> 00:11:10,582
My father died.

221
00:11:10,713 --> 00:11:12,149
Oh no!

222
00:11:16,545 --> 00:11:17,546
[ Sighs ]

223
00:11:21,419 --> 00:11:22,594
They, um...

224
00:11:22,725 --> 00:11:24,422
They don't know what happened.

225
00:11:24,553 --> 00:11:26,468
Some kind of accident
on the island.

226
00:11:27,687 --> 00:11:28,949
[ Sighs ]

227
00:11:29,079 --> 00:11:31,473
I know I wasn't very
close with him lately,

228
00:11:31,603 --> 00:11:34,041
but I didn't expect to...

229
00:11:34,171 --> 00:11:35,782
Oh, baby.

230
00:11:41,831 --> 00:11:44,616
This is so beautiful up here!

231
00:11:45,835 --> 00:11:48,229
I mean, it's...
it's breathtaking!

232
00:11:49,491 --> 00:11:50,884
It's inspiring.

233
00:11:51,014 --> 00:11:52,494
It's all right.

234
00:11:52,624 --> 00:11:54,626
George!

235
00:11:54,757 --> 00:11:57,412
I understand how you
feel about the house,

236
00:11:57,542 --> 00:12:00,284
but you can't hold the whole
state of Maine responsible!

237
00:12:00,415 --> 00:12:02,504
Well, maybe not the whole state.

238
00:12:02,634 --> 00:12:03,810
[ Nicky chuckles ]

239
00:12:05,507 --> 00:12:06,900
I should paint up here.

240
00:12:07,030 --> 00:12:08,553
OK, now don't get any ideas.

241
00:12:10,207 --> 00:12:12,427
We're up here to bury my father,

242
00:12:12,557 --> 00:12:14,037
put the house up for sale,

243
00:12:14,168 --> 00:12:16,257
and then get back to
Boston by next Monday.

244
00:12:30,227 --> 00:12:31,707
Oh, look at this place!

245
00:12:32,839 --> 00:12:34,231
And you grew up here.

246
00:12:34,362 --> 00:12:36,146
Well, I went to school out here.

247
00:12:36,277 --> 00:12:39,106
I, uh...
grew up out there.

248
00:12:41,151 --> 00:12:44,154
So that's it, then?
That's your father's island?

249
00:12:44,285 --> 00:12:45,677
That's it.

250
00:12:45,808 --> 00:12:47,462
Wickersham Island.

251
00:12:50,073 --> 00:12:53,337
Forty acres of nothing with
a house in the middle of it.

252
00:12:53,468 --> 00:12:55,600
So how do we get out there?

253
00:12:55,731 --> 00:12:57,646
It's no different
than the big city.

254
00:12:57,777 --> 00:12:59,561
We take a taxi.

255
00:13:04,218 --> 00:13:06,742
I didn't know you could
handle a boat like that!

256
00:13:06,873 --> 00:13:08,962
Yeah, well, it's all
part of the mystery

257
00:13:09,092 --> 00:13:10,746
that is Wickersham Island.

258
00:13:10,877 --> 00:13:12,095
It's kind of sexy.

259
00:13:12,226 --> 00:13:13,140
Yeah?

260
00:13:13,270 --> 00:13:14,141
[ Chuckles ]

261
00:13:21,409 --> 00:13:22,540
What's wrong?

262
00:13:24,238 --> 00:13:25,630
Just creeps me out.

263
00:13:25,761 --> 00:13:27,415
What does?

264
00:13:27,545 --> 00:13:29,373
The house.

265
00:13:29,504 --> 00:13:31,680
You know, there are
people in Shoal Harbour

266
00:13:31,811 --> 00:13:33,508
that actually
believe it's haunted.

267
00:14:03,712 --> 00:14:05,714
Oh my gosh.

268
00:14:07,847 --> 00:14:09,370
Look at this place!

269
00:14:11,502 --> 00:14:12,764
George!

270
00:14:12,895 --> 00:14:14,592
It's fantastic!

271
00:14:19,162 --> 00:14:20,555
When was it built?

272
00:14:20,685 --> 00:14:23,166
Uh, I think it was 1840.

273
00:14:23,297 --> 00:14:24,864
By my, uh...

274
00:14:24,994 --> 00:14:26,691
great-great-

275
00:14:26,822 --> 00:14:29,259
great-great-grandfather,

276
00:14:29,390 --> 00:14:31,174
Jebidiah Wickersham.

277
00:14:31,305 --> 00:14:32,219
I'm sorry.

278
00:14:32,349 --> 00:14:34,134
You're the descendant

279
00:14:34,264 --> 00:14:36,701
of a Jebidiah, and
you never told me?

280
00:14:37,877 --> 00:14:39,791
In most metropolitan cities,

281
00:14:39,922 --> 00:14:42,490
that could be
cause for annulment.

282
00:14:42,620 --> 00:14:46,929
Uh... yeah, well,
I was kind of really hoping

283
00:14:47,060 --> 00:14:49,192
that we could name
our first-born son, um...

284
00:14:50,498 --> 00:14:51,847
Jebidiah.

285
00:14:53,414 --> 00:14:55,895
No? 'Cause I'm
totally kidding.

286
00:14:57,418 --> 00:15:00,116
Seriously, even as
a joke, that is disturbing.

287
00:15:00,247 --> 00:15:02,205
I'm just trying
to lighten it up.

288
00:15:02,336 --> 00:15:03,467
I know.

289
00:15:06,166 --> 00:15:07,515
[ Footsteps ]

290
00:15:09,125 --> 00:15:10,518
Did you hear that?

291
00:15:11,867 --> 00:15:12,955
[ Footsteps ]

292
00:15:13,086 --> 00:15:14,652
Sounds like footsteps.

293
00:15:14,783 --> 00:15:16,393
Why would there...

294
00:15:18,526 --> 00:15:21,050
Sorry. Didn't mean
to frighten you.

295
00:15:21,181 --> 00:15:22,530
Who are you?

296
00:15:22,660 --> 00:15:24,880
Peter Hughes.
Caretaker. You George?

297
00:15:25,011 --> 00:15:26,577
Yes, I am.

298
00:15:26,708 --> 00:15:29,276
Your dad hired me a while ago
to keep an eye on the place.

299
00:15:29,406 --> 00:15:30,930
I live in the
servants' quarters.

300
00:15:31,060 --> 00:15:32,975
He didn't tell me
anything about you.

301
00:15:33,106 --> 00:15:35,978
Well, he didn't tell me
anything about you either.

302
00:15:37,284 --> 00:15:39,155
I was the one
who found him, you know.

303
00:15:40,722 --> 00:15:41,897
Over there.

304
00:15:42,028 --> 00:15:43,333
By the window.

305
00:15:50,384 --> 00:15:51,733
[ Clearing throat ]

306
00:15:58,740 --> 00:16:01,699
- How is that possible?
- It's easier than you think!

307
00:16:01,830 --> 00:16:03,049
He was getting on in years.

308
00:16:03,179 --> 00:16:04,964
He gets on that stool
to fix something...

309
00:16:05,094 --> 00:16:06,574
a broken curtain hook!

310
00:16:06,704 --> 00:16:08,619
And he reaches up,

311
00:16:08,750 --> 00:16:10,186
maybe a little too far!

312
00:16:10,317 --> 00:16:12,536
He loses his balance.
He gets tangled in the cord.

313
00:16:12,667 --> 00:16:14,103
It could all happen

314
00:16:14,234 --> 00:16:16,105
in a matter of seconds.

315
00:16:16,236 --> 00:16:18,151
There aren't any
broken hooks up there.

316
00:16:18,281 --> 00:16:20,370
I'm not saying I know
exactly how it happened.

317
00:16:20,501 --> 00:16:21,850
- Oh!
- The point is,

318
00:16:21,981 --> 00:16:25,201
George, your father died
in a tragic accident.

319
00:16:25,332 --> 00:16:27,029
What if it wasn't an accident?

320
00:16:27,160 --> 00:16:28,422
You saying he was murdered?

321
00:16:28,552 --> 00:16:30,946
Makes more sense, doesn't it?

322
00:16:31,077 --> 00:16:33,557
Who would wanna kill
your father, George?

323
00:16:33,688 --> 00:16:35,559
What about that...
that caretaker?

324
00:16:35,690 --> 00:16:37,779
Peter?
He's a good kid.

325
00:16:37,909 --> 00:16:39,955
Your father thought
the world of him!

326
00:16:40,086 --> 00:16:42,697
He was always
in trouble, no parents.

327
00:16:42,827 --> 00:16:45,265
The kid was on
a fast train to nowhere

328
00:16:45,395 --> 00:16:47,397
until George
straightened him out!

329
00:16:47,528 --> 00:16:49,312
He was devoted to your father.

330
00:16:49,443 --> 00:16:52,185
What if it was someone
that followed him out here,

331
00:16:52,315 --> 00:16:53,403
but that he didn't know?

332
00:16:53,534 --> 00:16:55,188
Someone coming
out to rob him, or...

333
00:16:55,318 --> 00:16:57,407
That's right. They could
still be on the island.

334
00:16:57,538 --> 00:16:58,539
Have you searched it?

335
00:16:58,669 --> 00:17:00,236
I'm sure down there in Boston,

336
00:17:00,367 --> 00:17:02,456
you got all kinds
of motives you could find

337
00:17:02,586 --> 00:17:04,371
for any accident
you stumble across.

338
00:17:04,501 --> 00:17:06,764
But up here, when
we hear the sound of hooves,

339
00:17:06,895 --> 00:17:09,463
we don't exactly
go looking for zebras.

340
00:17:09,593 --> 00:17:12,422
Yeah, well, apparently you
don't look for answers either.

341
00:17:12,553 --> 00:17:14,207
George!

342
00:17:14,337 --> 00:17:15,860
You're upset.

343
00:17:15,991 --> 00:17:18,037
You've been away a long time.

344
00:17:18,167 --> 00:17:22,084
We went over every
square inch of this island,

345
00:17:22,215 --> 00:17:24,478
and of course, this house.

346
00:17:24,608 --> 00:17:27,176
There was no evidence
whatsoever of foul play.

347
00:17:28,438 --> 00:17:30,571
It is what it appears
to be, George.

348
00:17:31,702 --> 00:17:32,834
A tragic accident.

349
00:17:34,183 --> 00:17:35,837
I personally prefer

350
00:17:35,967 --> 00:17:37,752
that scenario
to the alternative one,

351
00:17:37,882 --> 00:17:39,232
which is suicide.

352
00:17:43,018 --> 00:17:44,454
Thanks for the coffee, ma'am.

353
00:17:51,374 --> 00:17:52,593
Hi!

354
00:17:52,723 --> 00:17:54,899
Is this the servants'
quarters, where Peter stays?

355
00:17:55,030 --> 00:17:56,597
Stayed.

356
00:17:56,727 --> 00:17:59,991
I'm telling him he's out of here
when he gets back from town.

357
00:18:01,471 --> 00:18:02,559
OK.

358
00:18:04,257 --> 00:18:06,346
So you were raised
with servants, huh?

359
00:18:06,476 --> 00:18:07,869
[ Chuckles ]

360
00:18:07,999 --> 00:18:10,915
No. The old
Wickershams had servants,

361
00:18:11,046 --> 00:18:13,353
before the market
crashed in 1929.

362
00:18:14,571 --> 00:18:16,095
Were they really rich?

363
00:18:16,225 --> 00:18:17,792
Filthy.

364
00:18:17,922 --> 00:18:21,056
This place was actually built
to be their summer house.

365
00:18:21,187 --> 00:18:24,146
After the crash, they lost
everything but this place,

366
00:18:24,277 --> 00:18:26,279
so the family moved
out here permanently.

367
00:18:27,758 --> 00:18:29,934
Shortly after that,
my great-grandfather,

368
00:18:30,065 --> 00:18:31,762
the first George Wickersham...

369
00:18:33,634 --> 00:18:34,722
He died out here.

370
00:18:38,291 --> 00:18:40,380
So have all the Wickersham men.

371
00:18:44,906 --> 00:18:45,950
[ Thunderclap ]

372
00:18:53,784 --> 00:18:55,482
Grandpa Jebidiah?

373
00:18:55,612 --> 00:18:57,310
The grand patriarch?

374
00:18:57,440 --> 00:18:59,529
Yup, that's him.

375
00:18:59,660 --> 00:19:01,531
Good old Jeb Wickersham,

376
00:19:01,662 --> 00:19:04,360
who made the family fortune.

377
00:19:04,491 --> 00:19:06,319
Kind of like the Kennedys.

378
00:19:06,449 --> 00:19:08,234
He was like Joe, the father,

379
00:19:08,364 --> 00:19:10,149
except he didn't
make all his money

380
00:19:10,279 --> 00:19:11,715
running moonshine for the mob.

381
00:19:11,846 --> 00:19:13,108
[ Chuckles ]

382
00:19:14,544 --> 00:19:17,417
How did old Jeb
make his fortune?

383
00:19:17,547 --> 00:19:20,724
Um, he was a sailor
turned merchant

384
00:19:20,855 --> 00:19:22,378
who, as I understand it,

385
00:19:22,509 --> 00:19:26,252
became one of the
first shipping magnates.

386
00:19:26,382 --> 00:19:27,644
Hmm.

387
00:19:29,211 --> 00:19:30,473
[ Sighs ]

388
00:19:30,604 --> 00:19:31,953
George?

389
00:19:32,083 --> 00:19:33,172
Mmm?

390
00:19:35,043 --> 00:19:37,132
Do you think this
house is really haunted?

391
00:19:37,263 --> 00:19:38,655
[ Scoffs ]

392
00:19:40,135 --> 00:19:42,833
All I know is that
my grandfather thought so.

393
00:19:42,964 --> 00:19:44,357
[ Thunderclap ]

394
00:19:44,487 --> 00:19:45,445
[Both]: Oh!

395
00:19:46,881 --> 00:19:48,535
That's a nasty storm!

396
00:19:55,803 --> 00:19:57,239
Oh, for the...

397
00:19:57,370 --> 00:19:59,676
The generator just crapped out.

398
00:20:04,464 --> 00:20:05,595
George!

399
00:20:05,726 --> 00:20:07,597
I have a really bad
feeling about this.

400
00:20:07,728 --> 00:20:09,599
Can we just do
it in the morning?

401
00:20:09,730 --> 00:20:11,253
Not if we want power.

402
00:20:14,387 --> 00:20:15,997
I think I've found the problem.

403
00:20:16,127 --> 00:20:17,912
There's a loose wire
on the sparkplug.

404
00:20:18,042 --> 00:20:19,870
Will you pass me the pliers?

405
00:20:23,396 --> 00:20:25,049
I don't see pliers!

406
00:20:25,180 --> 00:20:27,443
They're up by the...
near the screwdriver tray.

407
00:20:27,574 --> 00:20:29,402
It's so dark,
I can't see anything.

408
00:20:29,532 --> 00:20:30,794
OK, look.

409
00:20:30,925 --> 00:20:32,187
Honey, they're right here.

410
00:20:32,318 --> 00:20:34,276
Look. Those are pliers.

411
00:20:34,407 --> 00:20:35,321
George!

412
00:20:40,543 --> 00:20:41,805
You guys all right?

413
00:20:41,936 --> 00:20:43,372
That thing could
have killed you!

414
00:20:43,503 --> 00:20:45,331
You! You did this!

415
00:20:45,461 --> 00:20:47,550
You pulled that wire
to get us out here!

416
00:20:47,681 --> 00:20:49,639
What the hell are
you talking about?

417
00:20:49,770 --> 00:20:52,686
I want you off this island
by the time the storm passes!

418
00:20:52,816 --> 00:20:53,774
Get out of here!

419
00:20:53,904 --> 00:20:54,905
George, calm down!

420
00:20:57,386 --> 00:20:59,258
Are you OK, baby?

421
00:21:04,785 --> 00:21:06,090
You saw him, Nicky.

422
00:21:06,221 --> 00:21:07,744
That sparkplug
wouldn't fall off.

423
00:21:07,875 --> 00:21:09,920
Someone loosened it,
and it wasn't you or me.

424
00:21:10,051 --> 00:21:12,706
But how would he know
when it was going to fall?

425
00:21:12,836 --> 00:21:14,708
Because he's the one
who loosened it!

426
00:21:14,838 --> 00:21:17,624
I think he killed my dad,
made it look like an accident,

427
00:21:17,754 --> 00:21:20,409
and then tried to do the same
thing to you and me last night.

428
00:21:22,281 --> 00:21:24,892
What would his motive be
for trying to kill your father?

429
00:21:25,022 --> 00:21:26,937
The bigger question
is what's his alibi?

430
00:21:27,068 --> 00:21:29,462
He told Sheriff Lindy he was
running an errand for Dad.

431
00:21:29,592 --> 00:21:31,420
Errand? Dad lived
in Shoal Harbour.

432
00:21:31,551 --> 00:21:34,249
Peter lived out on
the island. It doesn't add up.

433
00:21:34,380 --> 00:21:37,121
There's something more than
just an accident going on here,

434
00:21:37,252 --> 00:21:38,558
I can feel that.

435
00:21:38,688 --> 00:21:40,908
But how can we be sure
it wasn't a suicide?

436
00:21:41,038 --> 00:21:43,302
I mean, we don't know
your dad's state of mind.

437
00:21:45,042 --> 00:21:48,089
Listen, I know what
a suicide looks and feels like.

438
00:21:49,569 --> 00:21:51,658
I was in that house
when my grandfather...

439
00:21:52,963 --> 00:21:54,225
...killed himself.

440
00:21:55,662 --> 00:21:57,881
My dad told me that
it was an accident,

441
00:21:58,012 --> 00:22:00,928
that my grandfather was cleaning
his gun and it discharged,

442
00:22:01,058 --> 00:22:03,409
but what my dad didn't know
is that my grandfather

443
00:22:03,539 --> 00:22:05,628
was seeing things, and
secretly telling me.

444
00:22:05,759 --> 00:22:07,238
What things?

445
00:22:07,369 --> 00:22:08,979
The, um...

446
00:22:13,114 --> 00:22:16,465
The spirit of a woman.

447
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:21,644
Well then, that's how
the rumour got started.

448
00:22:21,775 --> 00:22:24,038
The rumour's been around
as long as the house.

449
00:22:24,168 --> 00:22:25,648
My mother thought my grandfather

450
00:22:25,779 --> 00:22:27,563
started believing
the haunting stories

451
00:22:27,694 --> 00:22:29,783
because, you know,
he lost his mind.

452
00:22:29,913 --> 00:22:31,262
Did you think he was crazy?

453
00:22:32,394 --> 00:22:34,309
He wasn't crazy.

454
00:22:34,440 --> 00:22:36,746
Anything that happened out there

455
00:22:36,877 --> 00:22:39,183
after that just
added to the legend.

456
00:22:41,055 --> 00:22:42,709
And that's what this...

457
00:22:42,839 --> 00:22:45,015
Peter is up to.

458
00:22:45,146 --> 00:22:48,497
He knows that if my dad's
death looks like an accident,

459
00:22:48,628 --> 00:22:50,543
people will just
blame it on the curse.

460
00:22:50,673 --> 00:22:53,023
Oh, my lands, is that Georgie 4?

461
00:22:54,155 --> 00:22:55,635
As I live and breathe,

462
00:22:55,765 --> 00:22:58,028
I didn't think I'd
ever see you again.

463
00:22:58,159 --> 00:22:59,856
Yeah, well...

464
00:22:59,987 --> 00:23:01,554
death happens.

465
00:23:01,684 --> 00:23:03,251
It certainly does.

466
00:23:03,382 --> 00:23:05,296
And I'm sorry for your loss.

467
00:23:05,427 --> 00:23:06,820
I truly am.

468
00:23:06,950 --> 00:23:08,909
I'm Nicky.

469
00:23:09,039 --> 00:23:10,214
I'm George's wife.

470
00:23:10,345 --> 00:23:12,434
- Sorry, this is...
- Virginia Roberts.

471
00:23:12,565 --> 00:23:15,176
You're every bit as pretty
as 3 said you were.

472
00:23:15,306 --> 00:23:17,700
You know, he carried your
wedding picture everywhere.

473
00:23:18,919 --> 00:23:20,094
Who's 3?

474
00:23:20,224 --> 00:23:21,922
Georgie 4's father.

475
00:23:22,052 --> 00:23:24,925
I named him 3 because he's
the 3rd George Wickersham.

476
00:23:25,055 --> 00:23:26,535
Well, that makes sense!

477
00:23:26,666 --> 00:23:27,754
[ Chuckles ]

478
00:23:27,884 --> 00:23:29,495
Hey, why don't you join us?

479
00:23:29,625 --> 00:23:32,149
Oh, I have to get back to
the shop. I don't have time.

480
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:34,630
And... and what
is it that you do?

481
00:23:34,761 --> 00:23:37,067
Oh, studio portraits,

482
00:23:37,198 --> 00:23:39,069
restorations,
little bit of everything.

483
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:40,375
You're a painter!

484
00:23:40,506 --> 00:23:41,637
No, no, photographs.

485
00:23:41,768 --> 00:23:43,509
I also run
photographic workshops.

486
00:23:43,639 --> 00:23:45,728
Excuse me. I have to
go use the restroom.

487
00:23:45,859 --> 00:23:47,077
I don't blame you

488
00:23:47,208 --> 00:23:48,775
for selling that place.

489
00:23:48,905 --> 00:23:50,298
Not one bit, Georgie 4.

490
00:23:53,606 --> 00:23:54,607
Please!

491
00:23:58,001 --> 00:23:59,350
So, Virginia,

492
00:23:59,481 --> 00:24:01,657
have you ever been
out to the island?

493
00:24:01,788 --> 00:24:04,094
Oh, my lands,
many times over the years.

494
00:24:04,225 --> 00:24:06,619
I've taken all
their family portraits.

495
00:24:06,749 --> 00:24:09,143
Ah. And what do you
think of the house?

496
00:24:09,273 --> 00:24:10,927
It's beautiful.

497
00:24:11,058 --> 00:24:13,626
I just hope whoever
buys it is told the truth.

498
00:24:14,757 --> 00:24:16,019
The truth?

499
00:24:16,150 --> 00:24:17,630
George hasn't told you?

500
00:24:17,760 --> 00:24:18,935
It's haunted!

501
00:24:20,154 --> 00:24:21,460
Oh yeah, so I've heard!

502
00:24:22,896 --> 00:24:25,464
But, uh... come on, Virginia.

503
00:24:25,594 --> 00:24:28,597
I mean... you don't
really believe that, do you?

504
00:24:31,165 --> 00:24:34,168
What I believe is irrelevant.

505
00:24:40,217 --> 00:24:42,611
I can't wait for you
to see it, Margie.

506
00:24:42,742 --> 00:24:44,395
It's so beautiful here!

507
00:24:46,746 --> 00:24:49,575
I'm inspired to draw
like I've never felt before!

508
00:24:50,750 --> 00:24:51,881
I'm so excited.

509
00:24:52,012 --> 00:24:53,796
I can use all the
inspiration I can get.

510
00:24:53,927 --> 00:24:55,842
Are there any good
wine stores up there?

511
00:24:55,972 --> 00:24:57,147
Um, no.

512
00:24:57,278 --> 00:24:59,019
Pack wisely, leave
your pumps at home.

513
00:24:59,149 --> 00:25:00,150
Come ready to write.

514
00:25:01,369 --> 00:25:03,110
Hey, any handsome neighbours

515
00:25:03,240 --> 00:25:04,981
looking for
desperate housewives?

516
00:25:05,112 --> 00:25:06,200
[ Chuckles ]

517
00:25:06,330 --> 00:25:08,028
It's an island, Margie.

518
00:25:08,158 --> 00:25:09,725
We'll be the only ones on it.

519
00:25:11,248 --> 00:25:12,946
Hope she doesn't
have too many bags.

520
00:25:13,076 --> 00:25:14,251
I know. She will, though.

521
00:25:14,382 --> 00:25:15,383
Love you!

522
00:25:17,211 --> 00:25:18,342
Margie!

523
00:25:19,474 --> 00:25:20,736
Nick! Hey!

524
00:25:23,043 --> 00:25:26,089
Listen, uh, I'll
catch up with you later.

525
00:25:26,220 --> 00:25:27,090
Yeah, you bet.

526
00:25:27,221 --> 00:25:28,178
OK!

527
00:25:30,267 --> 00:25:32,879
Oh my God, I can't
believe you own an island!

528
00:25:33,009 --> 00:25:35,055
I know. It's amazing, right?

529
00:25:35,185 --> 00:25:37,710
That's so cool! Billionaires
and movie stars have islands.

530
00:25:37,840 --> 00:25:39,102
What was he saying to you?

531
00:25:39,233 --> 00:25:40,539
Oh! Is he hot, or what?

532
00:25:40,669 --> 00:25:42,062
He was talking about

533
00:25:42,192 --> 00:25:44,891
some unfinished business
on the island or something.

534
00:25:45,021 --> 00:25:45,848
Hope it's me.

535
00:25:45,979 --> 00:25:47,154
Margie!

536
00:25:47,284 --> 00:25:48,459
- Hey!
- How's it going?

537
00:25:48,590 --> 00:25:49,504
Good.

538
00:25:49,635 --> 00:25:50,505
This everything?

539
00:25:50,636 --> 00:25:51,637
That's everything!

540
00:25:51,767 --> 00:25:53,464
Travelling light.
I'm surprised!

541
00:25:53,595 --> 00:25:54,640
Oh yeah!

542
00:26:04,040 --> 00:26:05,259
What are you doing here?

543
00:26:05,389 --> 00:26:06,869
I live here,
Mrs. Wickersham.

544
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:08,871
Remember?
I used to live out there.

545
00:26:09,002 --> 00:26:11,657
The night George's
father died, you left.

546
00:26:11,787 --> 00:26:13,484
Sorry, is that any
of your business?

547
00:26:13,615 --> 00:26:15,225
Don't have an alibi, do you?

548
00:26:15,356 --> 00:26:19,012
You don't need an alibi unless
you're accused of something.

549
00:26:19,142 --> 00:26:20,317
Nicky!

550
00:26:22,232 --> 00:26:23,843
Be careful on that island.

551
00:26:23,973 --> 00:26:26,149
Wickershams aren't
always welcome.

552
00:26:26,280 --> 00:26:29,065
I don't believe
in that curse story.

553
00:26:29,196 --> 00:26:31,111
I know someone
killed George's father,

554
00:26:31,241 --> 00:26:32,460
and I'm gonna find out who.

555
00:26:34,244 --> 00:26:35,985
Let me know if you do.

556
00:26:48,041 --> 00:26:49,433
How you holding up?

557
00:26:50,826 --> 00:26:52,698
I'm OK.

558
00:26:52,828 --> 00:26:55,091
I know I wasn't
very close with my dad

559
00:26:55,222 --> 00:26:56,615
when we were together, but...

560
00:27:00,270 --> 00:27:02,055
I really did love him.

561
00:27:03,578 --> 00:27:05,885
I never doubted that.

562
00:27:06,015 --> 00:27:08,278
It's just, after
my grandfather died,

563
00:27:08,409 --> 00:27:09,715
we just stopped talking.

564
00:27:09,845 --> 00:27:12,326
It was like he
shut the door on me.

565
00:27:12,456 --> 00:27:14,328
I always felt like he had a...

566
00:27:15,982 --> 00:27:18,854
...a sense of relief
when I left for college.

567
00:27:22,641 --> 00:27:24,860
I'm sorry you didn't
get a chance to meet him.

568
00:27:24,991 --> 00:27:26,862
He would have loved you.

569
00:27:32,476 --> 00:27:33,869
Your mom's there too?

570
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:34,914
Yeah.

571
00:27:37,133 --> 00:27:39,658
Half of Shoal Harbour
came out when we buried her.

572
00:27:39,788 --> 00:27:41,660
That was the saddest
day of my life.

573
00:27:44,010 --> 00:27:47,448
Grandparents, aunts, uncles,
they're all buried here.

574
00:27:49,145 --> 00:27:51,495
This graveyard is why I left.

575
00:27:53,628 --> 00:27:55,456
Made me feel like
I would die here, too.

576
00:27:57,545 --> 00:27:59,373
You're not gonna
die here, George.

577
00:28:00,940 --> 00:28:02,332
How can you be so sure?

578
00:28:05,031 --> 00:28:06,902
Because I'm an artist,

579
00:28:07,033 --> 00:28:09,426
and artists feel things
that non-artists can't.

580
00:28:11,602 --> 00:28:13,692
You're gonna grow old,

581
00:28:13,822 --> 00:28:15,998
and watch Georgie 5
have Georgie 6.

582
00:28:16,129 --> 00:28:17,217
[ Chuckling ]

583
00:28:19,436 --> 00:28:21,830
I think we have to
leave now, Georgie 4.

584
00:28:21,961 --> 00:28:23,049
Right. Thanks.

585
00:28:26,922 --> 00:28:29,055
Why don't you go
with them down to the dock,

586
00:28:29,185 --> 00:28:30,534
and I'll just meet you inside?

587
00:28:32,667 --> 00:28:33,886
God, I love you.

588
00:28:36,323 --> 00:28:37,541
Oh, I love you.

589
00:28:41,589 --> 00:28:42,721
[ Sighs ]

590
00:29:02,697 --> 00:29:04,655
What is this legacy of secrets

591
00:29:04,786 --> 00:29:07,441
that has my husband
so troubled, Jebidiah?

592
00:29:16,015 --> 00:29:18,757
Nothing like a good
old family funeral

593
00:29:18,887 --> 00:29:21,934
to bring out the best
and worst in people.

594
00:29:22,064 --> 00:29:23,544
Why are you here?

595
00:29:23,674 --> 00:29:25,328
To pay my respects.

596
00:29:25,459 --> 00:29:27,069
And to show you and your husband

597
00:29:27,200 --> 00:29:29,463
you're not as smart
as you think you are.

598
00:29:31,639 --> 00:29:34,163
I'm gonna trust you
keep this to yourself.

599
00:29:37,166 --> 00:29:39,778
I didn't know he was
coming here alone that night.

600
00:29:39,908 --> 00:29:41,649
Money order receipt?

601
00:29:41,780 --> 00:29:43,956
$83,000.

602
00:29:44,086 --> 00:29:47,046
That's all he had, except
for this house and island.

603
00:29:48,699 --> 00:29:49,788
Who's Pamela?

604
00:29:49,918 --> 00:29:51,398
The other woman.

605
00:29:54,270 --> 00:29:55,663
I don't understand.

606
00:29:55,794 --> 00:29:58,448
The old man had a girlfriend
who lives up the coast.

607
00:29:58,579 --> 00:30:00,973
Nobody knew, not even
me until that night.

608
00:30:01,103 --> 00:30:03,627
He asked me to give her that
money order with a letter.

609
00:30:03,758 --> 00:30:05,281
Said it was urgent.

610
00:30:05,412 --> 00:30:06,892
When I got back,

611
00:30:07,022 --> 00:30:08,328
he was already dead.

612
00:30:10,199 --> 00:30:11,766
So what was the big secret?

613
00:30:11,897 --> 00:30:14,029
He'd been seeing
her for 22 years.

614
00:30:14,160 --> 00:30:16,858
But he made me swear
not to tell anybody.

615
00:30:18,338 --> 00:30:20,340
I would have died for that man.

616
00:30:21,820 --> 00:30:23,299
He was like a father to me.

617
00:30:24,997 --> 00:30:26,563
I feel like
I'm betraying him now.

618
00:30:27,782 --> 00:30:29,828
But I can't let his only son

619
00:30:29,958 --> 00:30:31,612
think that I killed him.

620
00:30:31,742 --> 00:30:34,310
We owe you an apology, Peter.

621
00:30:34,441 --> 00:30:36,138
I would have thought
the same thing.

622
00:30:37,226 --> 00:30:38,140
Oh...

623
00:30:38,271 --> 00:30:39,663
I'd, uh,

624
00:30:39,794 --> 00:30:41,622
like to stop out tomorrow,
pick up my tools,

625
00:30:41,752 --> 00:30:43,363
if that'd be OK
with your husband.

626
00:30:43,493 --> 00:30:44,668
Of course, yeah.

627
00:30:44,799 --> 00:30:46,757
I'll talk to him.
I'm sure it'll be fine.

628
00:30:55,244 --> 00:30:57,943
I know it's a shock,
George, but it makes sense.

629
00:30:59,205 --> 00:31:00,684
Of course it makes sense.

630
00:31:03,165 --> 00:31:05,037
It's my family all over.

631
00:31:06,777 --> 00:31:08,127
Secrets and lies.

632
00:31:09,998 --> 00:31:11,521
God, I hate this place!

633
00:31:13,175 --> 00:31:14,481
[ Sighs ]

634
00:31:14,611 --> 00:31:16,613
I can't wait to sell this house

635
00:31:16,744 --> 00:31:18,877
and put this all behind us.

636
00:31:30,845 --> 00:31:32,542
You know what's sad,

637
00:31:32,673 --> 00:31:34,414
is George wanting
to sell this place.

638
00:31:34,544 --> 00:31:35,719
You can't let him!

639
00:31:35,850 --> 00:31:37,330
It's not my call.

640
00:31:37,460 --> 00:31:39,593
What are you talking
about? You're his wife!

641
00:31:41,334 --> 00:31:43,031
Can you believe this place

642
00:31:43,162 --> 00:31:45,468
has been in his family
since before the Civil War?

643
00:31:45,599 --> 00:31:47,209
I'll tell you what
do to. Divorce him.

644
00:31:47,340 --> 00:31:48,428
[ Chuckles ]

645
00:31:48,558 --> 00:31:49,995
No, hear me out.
You divorce.

646
00:31:50,125 --> 00:31:51,953
You get a great lawyer,
you divorce him,

647
00:31:52,084 --> 00:31:53,346
take the house and the island

648
00:31:53,476 --> 00:31:55,000
in a community
property settlement.

649
00:31:55,130 --> 00:31:56,479
He doesn't want it anyway.

650
00:31:56,610 --> 00:31:58,960
Then just remarry him
and do what you want with it!

651
00:31:59,091 --> 00:32:02,007
If you weren't certifiable,
I would consider it.

652
00:32:02,137 --> 00:32:03,312
[ Laughing ]

653
00:32:03,443 --> 00:32:05,401
I have been thinking, though.

654
00:32:05,532 --> 00:32:07,969
You know what I would really
love to do with this place?

655
00:32:08,100 --> 00:32:09,231
What?

656
00:32:09,362 --> 00:32:11,277
I'd love to turn it
into a retreat.

657
00:32:11,407 --> 00:32:13,583
You know, for artists.

658
00:32:13,714 --> 00:32:16,630
Like, painters and
writers and poets.

659
00:32:16,760 --> 00:32:19,633
Maybe work out something with
Wrenfield College, the students

660
00:32:19,763 --> 00:32:21,678
could come and
do a course for credit.

661
00:32:21,809 --> 00:32:23,550
Yeah. Oh, do it!

662
00:32:23,680 --> 00:32:25,682
You should absolutely do it.

663
00:32:25,813 --> 00:32:28,163
George wouldn't have
to be here, would he?

664
00:32:28,294 --> 00:32:30,165
OK, look. Maybe if
you just tell him

665
00:32:30,296 --> 00:32:32,167
what you wanted,
he would reconsider!

666
00:32:32,298 --> 00:32:34,735
I don't know.
He's pretty adamant.

667
00:32:34,865 --> 00:32:36,563
Oh, come on.
He is your husband.

668
00:32:36,693 --> 00:32:39,566
Give him one of those romantic
evenings guys just dream about,

669
00:32:39,696 --> 00:32:41,437
and he'll be adamant
that you do it.

670
00:32:41,568 --> 00:32:43,874
It doesn't work that way
once you're married.

671
00:32:44,005 --> 00:32:46,616
Oh, come on! It works that way
before, during and after.

672
00:32:46,747 --> 00:32:47,922
[ Giggles ]

673
00:32:50,577 --> 00:32:52,579
I need two good-size heads,

674
00:32:52,709 --> 00:32:55,103
about yea big, maybe this big.

675
00:32:55,234 --> 00:32:57,366
OK. Would you
rather go yourself?

676
00:32:57,497 --> 00:32:59,020
No, I need to
stay here. Work.

677
00:32:59,151 --> 00:33:01,196
Then go to work!
I got your list, Nicky.

678
00:33:01,327 --> 00:33:03,590
I'm pretty sure I can handle
a supply run on my own.

679
00:33:03,720 --> 00:33:05,026
OK.

680
00:33:05,157 --> 00:33:06,767
Well, lookee here!
Peter told me

681
00:33:06,897 --> 00:33:08,943
there was another Wickersham
back on the island.

682
00:33:09,074 --> 00:33:09,988
Hello, Mr. Trinkle.

683
00:33:10,118 --> 00:33:11,554
Sorry about your dad.

684
00:33:13,295 --> 00:33:14,601
One of a kind, that one.

685
00:33:16,037 --> 00:33:17,256
Thank you.

686
00:33:17,386 --> 00:33:19,345
Uh, Mr. Trinkle,
this is my wife, Nicky.

687
00:33:19,475 --> 00:33:21,042
Cal Trinkle!

688
00:33:21,173 --> 00:33:22,826
Shoal Harbour postmaster

689
00:33:22,957 --> 00:33:24,393
and rural route carrier.

690
00:33:24,524 --> 00:33:26,700
Nice to meet
you, Mr. Trinkle.

691
00:33:26,830 --> 00:33:28,963
I asked Cal for
a ride out to get my tools.

692
00:33:29,094 --> 00:33:31,400
Couldn't haul them in my kayak.
I hope you don't mind.

693
00:33:31,531 --> 00:33:32,793
It's fine.

694
00:33:32,923 --> 00:33:34,577
We used to come out here

695
00:33:34,708 --> 00:33:36,579
every Wednesday,
remember, George?

696
00:33:36,710 --> 00:33:39,278
Rain or shine, wind,
sleet, hail, snow,

697
00:33:39,408 --> 00:33:40,627
you know the poem!

698
00:33:40,757 --> 00:33:41,802
Yeah.

699
00:33:41,932 --> 00:33:43,499
You know, your mom never failed

700
00:33:43,630 --> 00:33:45,371
to offer me a bit of lunch!

701
00:33:46,720 --> 00:33:47,895
That's your cue.

702
00:33:48,026 --> 00:33:49,418
Oh!

703
00:33:49,549 --> 00:33:52,465
Um, would you care
for something to eat

704
00:33:52,595 --> 00:33:54,336
while Peter collects his things?

705
00:33:54,467 --> 00:33:56,643
Well, that's kind
of you, Mrs. Wickersham.

706
00:33:56,773 --> 00:33:58,906
I don't mind if you do!

707
00:33:59,037 --> 00:34:00,429
He doesn't mind if you do.

708
00:34:00,560 --> 00:34:02,170
- OK.
- Go. Enjoy your meal.

709
00:34:04,607 --> 00:34:05,478
Dearie?

710
00:34:05,608 --> 00:34:06,740
Yes?

711
00:34:06,870 --> 00:34:08,655
Thirty-five years,
every Wednesday!

712
00:34:08,785 --> 00:34:10,874
Nicky told me about Dad's...

713
00:34:12,267 --> 00:34:14,052
...situation.

714
00:34:14,182 --> 00:34:15,879
Thank you for your discretion.

715
00:34:18,317 --> 00:34:19,753
I loved your dad.

716
00:34:19,883 --> 00:34:21,929
I mean, I know I wasn't his son,

717
00:34:22,060 --> 00:34:24,671
but he was the closest thing
to a father that I ever had.

718
00:34:26,890 --> 00:34:29,545
That would make us,
uh, brothers, would it?

719
00:34:31,808 --> 00:34:33,723
God, I hope not.

720
00:34:33,854 --> 00:34:36,465
Come on, let's start over.
Good to meet you.

721
00:34:48,129 --> 00:34:49,261
Peter?

722
00:34:52,046 --> 00:34:53,221
Hello?

723
00:34:54,831 --> 00:34:56,529
Peter?

724
00:34:57,660 --> 00:34:58,705
Hey!

725
00:34:58,835 --> 00:35:01,011
Is everything all right?

726
00:35:01,142 --> 00:35:03,840
Yeah. We had a little talk.

727
00:35:03,971 --> 00:35:06,756
Your husband, he's, uh...
he's a nice guy.

728
00:35:06,887 --> 00:35:09,150
Well, I think so.

729
00:35:09,281 --> 00:35:12,501
It's too bad we had to meet
under these circumstances.

730
00:35:12,632 --> 00:35:14,286
I think his dad would have liked

731
00:35:14,416 --> 00:35:16,070
us all having
beers or something.

732
00:35:16,201 --> 00:35:17,027
Oh! Whoops!

733
00:35:17,158 --> 00:35:18,681
Sorry!

734
00:35:20,596 --> 00:35:21,597
What is that?

735
00:35:21,728 --> 00:35:23,208
I don't know.

736
00:35:25,079 --> 00:35:26,733
I didn't even know it was here.

737
00:35:34,262 --> 00:35:35,742
Kind of creepy, huh?

738
00:35:37,526 --> 00:35:38,484
Look at this... AH!

739
00:35:38,614 --> 00:35:39,615
[ Screams ]

740
00:35:39,746 --> 00:35:40,921
[ Laughs ]

741
00:35:41,051 --> 00:35:42,401
First time in here?

742
00:35:44,229 --> 00:35:46,709
Yes, it is my
first time in here.

743
00:35:46,840 --> 00:35:48,624
[ Laughs ]

744
00:35:48,755 --> 00:35:51,323
I kind of had this idea
to turn this place

745
00:35:51,453 --> 00:35:53,151
into, like,
a bunkhouse or something.

746
00:35:53,281 --> 00:35:54,500
A bunkhouse?

747
00:35:54,630 --> 00:35:57,242
You planning on
turning this place into a ranch?

748
00:35:57,372 --> 00:36:00,854
No, like more of
a retreat for artists.

749
00:36:00,984 --> 00:36:03,291
There you are!
What are you guys doing in here?

750
00:36:03,422 --> 00:36:04,901
I was telling him

751
00:36:05,032 --> 00:36:06,642
about my plans to renovate.

752
00:36:06,773 --> 00:36:08,166
Renovate, huh?

753
00:36:08,296 --> 00:36:09,950
You know, I'm pretty
good at doing that.

754
00:36:11,821 --> 00:36:15,173
We can put in a new door,
a kitchen area here,

755
00:36:15,303 --> 00:36:17,000
and a living room there.

756
00:36:17,131 --> 00:36:19,264
Sounds perfect.

757
00:36:19,394 --> 00:36:21,614
Sounds like a pretty
expensive renovation.

758
00:36:21,744 --> 00:36:24,269
Not really. It's mostly
just paint and plaster.

759
00:36:24,399 --> 00:36:26,358
Yeah, but what
about your labour?

760
00:36:26,488 --> 00:36:29,535
Ah, we'll just call it
a wash for 5 years of free rent.

761
00:36:29,665 --> 00:36:31,624
Are you serious?

762
00:36:31,754 --> 00:36:33,103
Yeah, why not?

763
00:36:33,234 --> 00:36:35,671
I've always wanted
to start my own company.

764
00:36:35,802 --> 00:36:37,107
Shoal Harbour Renovations.

765
00:36:37,238 --> 00:36:38,848
This could be
the job to launch it.

766
00:36:38,979 --> 00:36:40,763
Well, sounds great!

767
00:36:40,894 --> 00:36:42,852
I just have to get
George on board first.

768
00:36:42,983 --> 00:36:45,203
How you gonna do that?

769
00:36:46,726 --> 00:36:48,031
One step at a time.

770
00:36:48,162 --> 00:36:49,511
[ Laughing ]

771
00:36:53,776 --> 00:36:54,690
Hey!

772
00:36:54,821 --> 00:36:55,909
Hey.

773
00:36:57,998 --> 00:36:59,652
So, I'm gonna ask you something.

774
00:36:59,782 --> 00:37:01,480
OK.

775
00:37:01,610 --> 00:37:04,483
And I realize that
it is insensitive,

776
00:37:04,613 --> 00:37:07,573
and maybe, you know,
out of line, but...

777
00:37:08,704 --> 00:37:10,097
I gotta ask!

778
00:37:13,056 --> 00:37:14,623
How would you feel

779
00:37:14,754 --> 00:37:18,105
about me staying here
for a little while?

780
00:37:19,672 --> 00:37:20,890
Oh, Nick.

781
00:37:21,021 --> 00:37:23,371
OK, wait. Wait, wait.

782
00:37:23,502 --> 00:37:26,592
I could make myself
available to the realtor,

783
00:37:26,722 --> 00:37:29,072
maybe spruce the place
up a little bit.

784
00:37:29,203 --> 00:37:31,292
You go back to Boston, work,

785
00:37:31,423 --> 00:37:34,991
and I can stay up here and...

786
00:37:36,254 --> 00:37:37,167
Explore!

787
00:37:37,298 --> 00:37:38,560
Explore what?

788
00:37:38,691 --> 00:37:39,909
Well, Celia said

789
00:37:40,040 --> 00:37:42,172
that my new work needed
to be more passionate.

790
00:37:42,303 --> 00:37:45,654
This place...
inspires the passion!

791
00:37:45,785 --> 00:37:47,047
[ Scoffs ]

792
00:37:47,177 --> 00:37:48,657
I just... I wanna paint up here.

793
00:37:50,180 --> 00:37:52,922
Just for a little while,
just to see how it goes.

794
00:37:53,053 --> 00:37:54,315
No.

795
00:37:59,277 --> 00:38:00,278
OK.

796
00:38:00,408 --> 00:38:01,627
Really?

797
00:38:01,757 --> 00:38:03,629
It's not like you asked me

798
00:38:03,759 --> 00:38:05,500
to not sell the place.

799
00:38:06,762 --> 00:38:07,894
Besides, who am I

800
00:38:08,024 --> 00:38:11,158
to question the muse
of an artist, huh?

801
00:38:11,289 --> 00:38:14,553
I'll leave early on Friday,
and be back up here by night.

802
00:38:14,683 --> 00:38:15,728
[ Chuckles ]

803
00:38:17,120 --> 00:38:18,470
You're the best, George.

804
00:38:18,600 --> 00:38:19,819
Mm-hmm.

805
00:38:21,951 --> 00:38:23,431
